## Anti-Patterns for Shared Utilities

```typescript
// âŒ Don't use 'any' types in shared utilities
export function badQuery(options: any): any { }

// âŒ Don't hard-code pagination limits
export function badPagination(page: number) {
  return query.limit(10); // Should be configurable
}

// âŒ Don't create utilities without proper generics
export function badUtility(query: PgSelect) {
  // Loses type information
}

// âŒ Don't mix pagination logic in domain-specific queries
export function getUsersWithPagination() {
  // Should use withPagination utility instead
}

// âŒ Don't use sequential await for independent operations
export async function badParallelQueries() {
  const users = await getUsersQuery();     // Waits unnecessarily
  const count = await getCountQuery();     // Could run in parallel
  return { users, count };
}

// âœ… Use Promise.all for independent operations
export async function goodParallelQueries() {
  const [users, count] = await Promise.all([
    getUsersQuery(),
    getCountQuery()
  ]);
  return { users, count };
}
```

## When to Add New Shared Types

Add new utilities to `shared-types/` when:
- âœ… The pattern is used in 3+ different queries
- âœ… The utility provides type safety benefits
- âœ… The pattern has reusable business logic
- âœ… It improves consistency across the codebase

Don't add to `shared-types/` when:
- âŒ The utility is domain-specific to one feature
- âŒ It's a simple wrapper without added value
- âŒ The pattern is unlikely to be reused

